hey get what they want out of their raid, then great; if not let them sign up again.  But not as a rotated slot. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#313532><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uxaeryaare.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Xaer YaAre</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Traveller of Underfoot</span><br> <font color=#CC9900>(5/28/01 8:57:44 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://members.theglobe.com/XaerYaare/GROEN.JPG WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Indies on Dragon Rotations</span><hr size=1> Sstiyrr, I do not understand your logic... Indy means individual, not guild.  If someone from your guild is on the rotation, they represent your guild and not themselves.  Nobody is going to support &quot;stacking&quot; the rotation list if people vote yes.  It doesn't happen now, and it won't happen in the future.  Trust me - if you try this, I don't want to be around to see the flames.<br>
<br>
I cannot see any justification for saying no to or limiting the rights of individuals to be on a dragon rotation.<br>
<br>
Slayback, for example, led a successful raid last time as an individual, and everyone had fun.  I fully support his right to be on the rotation again if he so chooses, and I would  be honored to help him slay the leezard.  Several guilds on the rotation will never ask for help - this trend will grow.  If you ban individuals from rotations, you will essentially close dragons off from the rest of Brell, which means: smaller guilds, independant players, and those that cannot afford to play as much as they would like to.  This is unconscionable.<br>
<br>
